;; ch16-whole-adventure.book.slatl
;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 16: The Whole Adventure

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      16
  :title               "The Whole Adventure"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :PG
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"You have all the tools. You have Cortex, story trees, dialogue trees,
body language, camera, audio, puzzles, inventory, world-state, the
companion. You have shipped fifteen small games as you worked through
this book.

Now you write a real one. Twenty scenes. Three endings. Five
characters. One villain. At least one puzzle. At least one moment of
quiet. This chapter walks you through the process — from blank page
to a working game a friend plays.

The example we build is called The Beekeeper's Daughter. You can
follow it exactly. Or you can build your own game about anything,
using this chapter as scaffolding. Either way, by the end you have a
game you can share with a friend.

---

## 16.1 The pitch

One paragraph before any code. Write your game's pitch.

*The beekeeper's daughter is missing. She left a note that said 'I am
at the beehive; do not worry about the honey.' You are her older
sibling. You come home from six months away. You find the note. You
have three days before the winter. You will not find her by the
hive. You have to figure out where she meant. The village will help
you or not, depending on how you have been.*

That's the pitch. Every scene must serve it. Every character must
either help you find her, complicate the search, or teach you
something about who you were when you were away.

If you can't write a pitch in one paragraph, you don't have a game
yet. Write and rewrite until it fits.

---

## 16.2 The consequence table

Before writing any scene, fill in the consequence table.

```
CHOICE                          IMMEDIATE                DOWNSTREAM
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
ch2: heal the fox               fox thanks               ch11: fox helps
     kill the fox                fox dies                 ch11: cold feeling
     walk past                   nothing                  ch11: nothing

ch3: give letter to Mira        Mira reads               ch9: Mira acts
     keep it                     you keep it              ch9: alternate
     burn it                     ash                       ch12: guilt

ch5: eat the honey              hunger sated             ch14: mother notices
     give it to beggar           small blessing            ch14: beggar helps
     leave it                    no change                 —

ch6: talk with Rowan             +2 Rowan reputation      ch13: Rowan helps
     avoid Rowan                  0                        ch13: Rowan absent

ch8: sit with the cat            +1 cat rep                ch15: cat leads
     scare it away                cat gone                  —

ch10: attend the wedding         +3 village rep           ch14: village helps
      skip                        -1                        ch14: village cold

ch11: read mother's diary        +1 knowledge             ch15: figure out place
      leave it                    no clue                   ch15: guess
```

Seven choices with real downstream effects. Each one is a Cortex
flag we set at the choice point and read later.

Fill this in before you write scene 2. It will save you hours of
retro-fitting.

---

## 16.3 The story tree

Now build the story tree. Twenty scenes.

```scheme
(define beekeepers-daughter-story
  '((:id ch01-arrival
     :text \"You arrive home after six months. The house is empty. On\n         the counter is a note in your sister's writing.\"
     :choices ((:label \"read the note\" :goto ch02-note)))

    (:id ch02-note
     :text \"'I am at the beehive. Do not worry about the honey. I\n         will be back before you get bored.' A fox in the yard,\n         limping.\"
     :choices ((:label \"heal the fox\"      :goto ch02-heal)
               (:label \"leave the fox\"     :goto ch02-leave)
               (:label \"read again\"        :goto ch02-note)))

    (:id ch02-heal
     :text \"You bandage the fox's leg. She watches you the whole\n         time. When you're done, she trots into the treeline.\"
     :choices ((:label \"walk into the village\" :goto ch03-village)))

    (:id ch02-leave
     :text \"You leave the fox to itself. It watches you go.\"
     :choices ((:label \"walk into the village\" :goto ch03-village)))

    (:id ch03-village
     :text \"The square. Mira is at the well. She has aged. She has a\n         letter in her hand.\"
     :choices ((:label \"take the letter\"  :goto ch03-letter)
               (:label \"leave the letter\" :goto ch03-refuse)))

    (:id ch03-letter
     :text \"The letter is from your mother, addressed to your sister.\n         Mira says: 'She left it here to be delivered.'\"
     :choices ((:label \"give it to your sister when you find her\" :goto ch03-keep)
               (:label \"read it now\"                                :goto ch03-read)
               (:label \"burn it\"                                    :goto ch03-burn)))

    (:id ch03-refuse
     :text \"Mira watches you go. She looks small.\"
     :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch04-hive)))

    (:id ch03-keep    :text \"You put the letter in your pocket.\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch04-hive)))
    (:id ch03-read    :text \"You read what your mother wrote. She wanted to tell your sister she was proud.\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch04-hive)))
    (:id ch03-burn    :text \"The letter goes to ash in the campfire. You do not know why you did that.\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch04-hive)))

    (:id ch04-hive
     :text \"The beehive. Undisturbed. She was not here today. She\n         was not here yesterday either.\"
     :choices ((:label \"look around\" :goto ch05-honeypot)
               (:label \"back to town\" :goto ch06-tavern)))

    (:id ch05-honeypot
     :text \"A honeypot with a broken lid. Someone has been here in\n         the past week but not today.\"
     :choices ((:label \"eat some honey\"     :goto ch05-eat)
               (:label \"give it to the beggar you passed\" :goto ch05-give)
               (:label \"leave it\"           :goto ch05-leave)))

    (:id ch05-eat    :text \"Sweet. You feel guilty as you swallow.\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch06-tavern)))
    (:id ch05-give   :text \"The beggar's face changes. He whispers a name — 'Rowan.'\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch06-tavern)))
    (:id ch05-leave  :text \"You leave the honeypot. It sits alone in the light.\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch06-tavern)))

    (:id ch06-tavern
     :text \"The tavern. Rowan sits alone at the corner table. He\n         looks up when you enter.\"
     :choices ((:label \"sit with Rowan\" :goto ch06-rowan)
               (:label \"pass by\"        :goto ch07-diary)))

    (:id ch06-rowan
     :text \"Rowan tells you: 'She's been asking about the old cabin\n         at the ridge. I told her to be careful.'\"
     :choices ((:label \"thank him\" :goto ch07-diary)))

    (:id ch07-diary
     :text \"Home again. Your mother's diary is on the shelf. Would\n         it be right to read it?\"
     :choices ((:label \"read the diary\"       :goto ch07-read)
               (:label \"leave it\"             :goto ch08-cat)))

    (:id ch07-read
     :text \"There is a passage: 'the ridge cabin is my grandmother's.\n         If anything happens, she'll go there.'\"
     :choices ((:label \"take the diary\" :goto ch08-cat)))

    (:id ch08-cat
     :text \"The kitchen cat sits on the stair. Watching you.\"
     :choices ((:label \"sit with her a moment\" :goto ch09-mira)
               (:label \"pass\"                  :goto ch09-mira)))

    (:id ch09-mira
     :text \"Mira again — at your door this time. 'The mother's\n         letter,' she asks. 'You still have it?'\"
     :choices ((:label \"give it\"      :goto ch09-give)
               (:label \"say you don't\" :goto ch09-refuse)))

    (:id ch09-give    :text \"Mira takes it. Her hands shake. 'Come with me,' she says.\" :choices ((:label \"go\" :goto ch10-wedding)))
    (:id ch09-refuse  :text \"Mira nods slowly and walks away.\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch10-wedding)))

    (:id ch10-wedding
     :text \"A village wedding is happening today. You could go.\"
     :choices ((:label \"attend\"    :goto ch10-attend)
               (:label \"skip\"      :goto ch11-fox)))

    (:id ch10-attend :text \"You dance. People remember you. You are less alone.\" :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch11-fox)))

    (:id ch11-fox
     :text \"You are at the edge of the woods. There is movement.\"
     :choices ((:label \"look\" :goto ch11-fox-appears)))

    (:id ch11-fox-appears
     :text \"[if you healed the fox in ch2, she is here]\"
     :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch12-guilt)))

    (:id ch12-guilt
     :text \"[if you burned the letter in ch3, you feel it here]\"
     :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch13-companion)))

    (:id ch13-companion
     :text \"The old woman on the road. 'You are close,' she says. 'Do\n         you want to sit for a moment?'\"
     :choices ((:label \"yes\" :goto ch13-reflect)
               (:label \"no\"  :goto ch14-approach)))

    (:id ch13-reflect
     :text \"[the deep-think reflection]\"
     :choices ((:label \"continue\" :goto ch14-approach)))

    (:id ch14-approach
     :text \"The ridge. You can see the cabin now.\"
     :choices ((:label \"approach\" :goto ch15-cabin)))

    (:id ch15-cabin
     :text \"The cabin door is open. She is inside. Alive.\"
     :choices ((:label \"embrace\" :goto ch16-end-embrace)
               (:label \"ask why\" :goto ch16-end-question)
               (:label \"stand there\" :goto ch16-end-still)))

    (:id ch16-end-embrace  :text \"You hold her. That is enough. That is the ending you chose.\" :choices ())
    (:id ch16-end-question :text \"'Why did you leave?' — she starts to answer. The story continues offscreen.\" :choices ())
    (:id ch16-end-still    :text \"You stand at the door. You do not know what to say. She looks at you. You are here.\" :choices ())))
```

Twenty scenes across sixteen chapter-nodes. Three endings —
embrace, ask, stand still. Each ending reflects a different way of
being with your sister when you find her.

Notice several scenes reference past choices — 'if you healed the
fox, she is here' at ch11. In the actual implementation those become
runtime `(cortex/read 'state/fox)` checks.

---

## 16.4 Wire the story

Load the story into the engine we built in chapter 2 and add the
extensions from chapters 3-15.

```scheme
;; The full runtime for the beekeeper's daughter.
(define (run-beekeepers-daughter)
  (setup-characters)
  (setup-audio)
  (play-node-with-all-features beekeepers-daughter-story 'ch01-arrival))

(define (setup-characters)
  (define mira    (make-character 'mira))
  (define rowan   (make-character 'rowan))
  (define mother  (make-character 'mother-in-diary))  ;; only in memory
  (define sister  (make-character 'sister))
  (define old-woman (make-character 'old-woman))
  ;; ... breath rates, sprites, etc.
  )

(define (setup-audio)
  (audio/play 'village-ambient :loop? #t :volume 0.15)
  ;; motifs, etc.
  )
```

The `play-node-with-all-features` variant of our engine is one that
supports Cortex reads at nodes, part-verb reactions, camera moves,
audio cues, and the companion. It's built up from the earlier
chapters' versions.

Chapter 2 has the base engine. Chapters 3-15 have the layers to add
to it. Add them as you need them; you don't need every feature in
every game.

---

## 16.5 Package as a card

```scheme
(define-card 'beekeepers-daughter
  :title \"the beekeeper's daughter\"
  :author \"[your name]\"
  :estimated-time \"25-40 minutes\"
  :audience :teen-and-up
  :init run-beekeepers-daughter)
```

The card wraps the whole game. It has metadata — title, author,
estimated play time. When you or a friend loads the card, the runtime
calls `run-beekeepers-daughter` and the game begins.

---

## 16.6 Publish to a share URL

```scheme
;; Publish the card. Returns a share URL.
(define my-url (define-card-publish 'beekeepers-daughter))

;; my-url is something like:
;;   https://motoi.example/play/abcd1234
```

The share URL takes the card and packages it as a self-contained
runnable. Anyone with the URL can play. They don't need to install
Motoi Scheme. They just click the link.

Appendix L walks through the publishing steps and the per-player
Cortex isolation.

---

## 16.7 Playtest

Send the URL to three friends. Ask each of them:

- Which ending did you get?
- What was the moment you felt most alive?
- Where did you get bored?
- Was there a choice that felt fake — like it didn't matter?
- Would you play it again?

Take their answers seriously. Notice patterns. If all three friends
got bored at ch7, that scene needs work. If all three felt the ch3
letter choice was fake, add real downstream consequences.

Do NOT argue with playtest feedback. Their experience is data. Your
intent is not their experience. Fix the game.

---

## 16.8 Debrief and iterate

After playtest, write down:

- What surprised you.
- What didn't work.
- What you would change.

The Beekeeper's Daughter is your first real narrative game. It will
have flaws. That's fine. Ship it, notice the flaws, iterate.

The NEXT one will be better BECAUSE of this one. The learning is in
having shipped, not in having planned perfectly. Ship the imperfect
one. Learn. Ship the next one.

---

## 16.9 Common desktop tasks — an operator's flagship story-cart

An operator has been running her shop for two years. She writes a
long story-cart called 'How the Shop Came To Be' — 15 scenes about
starting the shop, the first customer, the piece she almost gave
up on, the moment she knew she would keep going. Available to
customers who click a small 'about' link.

She uses everything: dialogue trees for the conversations she
remembers, body-language for the customers who taught her something,
sound cues for the workshop, the companion for one reflective
moment at the end. Playtime: 12 minutes.

She launches it. Repeat customers watch it. Some cry a little. Some
buy a piece afterward. All of them remember the shopkeeper as a
person, not a brand.

The story becomes part of what the shop IS. Not a marketing
document. A story.

---

## 16.10 Closing

You wrote a game. You published it. Someone else played it. Someone
told you what they felt.

That is the whole arc of this book. Everything else — the tools,
the appendices, the technique — served this moment.

Now write another one. The next one will be better. It will
probably be about something you didn't know you cared about until
you started writing it. That is how games about people work.

Thank you for reading this book. Send the URL to a friend. The
kid from north Georgia is out there somewhere; he needs the game
you just made.")
